---
to: tests/lsp_max_rule_pack_sparql_derived_proof.rs
sparql:
  rules: >
    PREFIX lm: <http://seanchatmangpt.github.io/packs/lsp-max#>
    SELECT ?ruleId ?name ?severity ?pattern ?pathGlobs ?excludeGlobs ?evalBudget ?message ?rationale
    WHERE {
      ?rule a lm:LintRule ;
            lm:ruleId       ?ruleId ;
            lm:name         ?name ;
            lm:severity     ?severity ;
            lm:pattern      ?pattern ;
            lm:pathGlobs    ?pathGlobs ;
            lm:excludeGlobs ?excludeGlobs ;
            lm:evalBudget   ?evalBudget ;
            lm:message      ?message ;
            lm:rationale    ?rationale .
    }
    ORDER BY ?ruleId
---
//! Generated by lsp-max-pack. Do not edit.
//!
//! SECOND proof, ALONGSIDE `rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl` (never a replacement
//! for it -- both are generated by every `ggen sync run`). That sibling
//! proof hand-transcribes its `EXPECTED_RULES` array from `ontology.ttl`
//! and deliberately carries no `sparql:` frontmatter key, for a real,
//! disclosed reason (its own header): re-deriving expectations through the
//! SAME query, in the SAME sync execution, that produced the artifact
//! under test would make the test agree with itself by construction. That
//! reasoning is correct for what THAT proof checks -- "does the generated
//! rule pack still parse, and does each pattern actually match/reject the
//! real code smell it claims to, exercised with real `toml`/`regex`
//! parsing against literal positive/negative snippets" -- but it leaves a
//! gap: a hand-transcribed array is authored once, directly into
//! `rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl`'s own template source, and never auto-updates
//! from a query -- so it cannot detect the case where `ontology.ttl`
//! changes LATER (a `lm:pattern`/`lm:message`/`lm:severity`/... edit) and
//! nobody remembers to hand-edit the sibling template's `EXPECTED_RULES`
//! entry to match.
//!
//! This proof closes that gap by checking a DIFFERENT thing, not the same
//! thing more strictly: whether `rules/lsp_max_*.toml` and
//! `docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md`, as they actually sit on disk right now,
//! still agree with what `lm:LintRule` individuals say RIGHT NOW. It
//! cannot and does not claim to validate "is the ontology itself correct"
//! -- nothing can, that is definitional -- only "has the checked-in
//! generated artifact silently drifted from the ontology since it was
//! last written."
//!
//! ## Why this is not the same tautology the sibling proof's header warns about
//!
//! 1. Template-source-literal staleness, not freeze-policy-induced
//!    staleness. Unlike `praxis-core-pack`/`star-toml-pack`'s
//!    generated-source templates, neither `rule_pack.toml.tmpl` nor
//!    `rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl` carries a `freeze_policy` key -- every
//!    `ggen sync run` unconditionally regenerates both `rules/lsp_max_*.toml`
//!    (live, from the `rules` query) and `tests/lsp_max_rule_pack_proof.rs`
//!    (from `rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl`'s own literal Rust source text, which
//!    contains no query at all). That second regeneration is the gap:
//!    rendering a template whose body is already a fixed string reproduces
//!    that fixed string byte-for-byte every time, regardless of what
//!    `ontology.ttl` now says -- the `EXPECTED_RULES` array only changes
//!    when a human opens `rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl` itself and edits its
//!    literal Rust source to match. This template carries NO such literal:
//!    its `LIVE_RULES` array below is re-baked from a live query against
//!    whatever `ontology.ttl` says at the moment THIS file is (re)generated,
//!    with no human edit step required to stay current.
//! 2. Independent rendering, not the same substitution checked twice. This
//!    template's own for-loop over the `rules` SPARQL result is a SEPARATE
//!    Tera render pass from `rule_pack.toml.tmpl`'s per-row
//!    `to:`-interpolated rendering and `rule_pack_index.md.tmpl`'s own loop
//!    over the identical query. A field-mapping bug local to ONE of these
//!    templates (wrong variable, dropped row, stray whitespace) produces a
//!    generated-artifact string that this proof's independently-rendered
//!    `LIVE_RULES` values will not match, and the assertions below fail --
//!    mirroring the same "two independent renderings checked against each
//!    other" principle the sibling proof already uses between its TOML and
//!    Markdown assertions, extended here to a freshly-queried third
//!    rendering instead of a third hand-typed one.
//!
//! ## Honest scope
//!
//! This still compares rendered TEXT via substring search, not parsed
//! TOML/Markdown, and it does not repeat the sibling proof's real
//! `regex`-compiles-and-matches exercises against positive/negative code
//! snippets (that is that proof's job; duplicating it here would be scope
//! creep, not a second check). It cannot prove ggen's own SPARQL/Tera
//! pipeline is bug-free in some absolute sense -- only that, on the sync
//! run that (re)generated this file, the live ontology and the checked-in
//! generated artifacts said the same thing. The fan-out
//! `rules/lsp_max_*.toml` files have no single deterministic on-disk order
//! (one file per rule, read back via `std::fs::read_dir`, whose entry order
//! is filesystem-dependent) -- unlike the reference packs' single-file
//! artifacts, so the `ORDER BY ?ruleId` regression guard below checks only
//! `docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md` (a single file whose row order IS
//! deterministic, written by `rule_pack_index.md.tmpl`'s own loop over the
//! identical `ORDER BY`).

use std::fs;
use std::path::Path;

/// One `lm:LintRule` individual as of the sync run that generated THIS
/// file, freshly baked from the `rules` SPARQL result -- never hand-typed.
struct LiveRule {
    rule_id: &'static str,
    name: &'static str,
    severity: &'static str,
    pattern: &'static str,
    path_globs: &'static [&'static str],
    exclude_globs: &'static [&'static str],
    eval_budget: &'static str,
    message: &'static str,
    rationale: &'static str,
}

const LIVE_RULES: &[LiveRule] = &[
{% for row in rules %}    LiveRule {
        rule_id: "{{ row.ruleId }}",
        name: "{{ row.name }}",
        severity: "{{ row.severity }}",
        pattern: r"{{ row.pattern }}",
        path_globs: &[{% for g in row.pathGlobs | split(pat=" ") %}"{{ g }}"{% if not loop.last %}, {% endif %}{% endfor %}],
        exclude_globs: &[{% for g in row.excludeGlobs | split(pat=" ") %}"{{ g }}"{% if not loop.last %}, {% endif %}{% endfor %}],
        eval_budget: "{{ row.evalBudget }}",
        message: "{{ row.message }}",
        rationale: "{{ row.rationale }}",
    },
{% endfor %}];

/// Concatenation of every generated `rules/lsp_max_*.toml` file's content,
/// read fresh at test-run time. Unlike the reference packs' single-file
/// `include_str!` targets, `rule_pack.toml.tmpl` fans out one file per
/// `lm:LintRule` individual (`rules/lsp_max_{ruleId | snake_case}.toml`),
/// so there is no single statically-known path to `include_str!` here.
/// Entries are sorted by filename before concatenation so this function's
/// own output is deterministic across runs, independent of
/// `std::fs::read_dir`'s filesystem-dependent iteration order.
fn all_generated_rule_toml() -> String {
    let dir = Path::new("rules");
    let mut entries: Vec<_> = fs::read_dir(dir)
        .unwrap_or_else(|e| {
            panic!(
                "expected {} to exist (generated by lsp-max-pack's rule_pack.toml.tmpl): {e}",
                dir.display()
            )
        })
        .map(|e| e.expect("readable rules/ dir entry").path())
        .filter(|p| {
            p.file_name()
                .and_then(|n| n.to_str())
                .is_some_and(|n| n.starts_with("lsp_max_") && n.ends_with(".toml"))
        })
        .collect();
    entries.sort();

    let mut combined = String::new();
    for path in entries {
        combined.push_str(
            &fs::read_to_string(&path)
                .unwrap_or_else(|e| panic!("reading {}: {e}", path.display())),
        );
        combined.push('\n');
    }
    combined
}

const MD_CONTENT: &str = include_str!("../docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md");

fn assert_rule_in_toml(toml_content: &str, rule: &LiveRule) {
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("id = \"{}\"", rule.rule_id)),
        "live ontology has rule `{}` but no generated rules/lsp_max_*.toml file declares \
         `id = \"{}\"` -- generated rule pack has drifted behind ontology.ttl",
        rule.rule_id, rule.rule_id
    );
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("name = \"{}\"", rule.name)),
        "live ontology says {} has name `{}` but no generated rules/lsp_max_*.toml file \
         contains that pairing -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.name
    );
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("severity = \"{}\"", rule.severity)),
        "live ontology says {} has severity `{}` but no generated rules/lsp_max_*.toml \
         file contains that pairing -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.severity
    );
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("pattern = '{}'", rule.pattern)),
        "live ontology says {} has pattern `{}` but no generated rules/lsp_max_*.toml \
         file contains that pairing -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.pattern
    );
    let path_globs_toml = rule
        .path_globs
        .iter()
        .map(|g| format!("\"{g}\""))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join(", ");
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("path_globs = [{path_globs_toml}]")),
        "live ontology says {} has path_globs {:?} but no generated rules/lsp_max_*.toml \
         file contains `path_globs = [{path_globs_toml}]` -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.path_globs
    );
    let exclude_globs_toml = rule
        .exclude_globs
        .iter()
        .map(|g| format!("\"{g}\""))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join(", ");
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("exclude_globs = [{exclude_globs_toml}]")),
        "live ontology says {} has exclude_globs {:?} but no generated \
         rules/lsp_max_*.toml file contains `exclude_globs = [{exclude_globs_toml}]` -- \
         drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.exclude_globs
    );
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("eval_budget = \"{}\"", rule.eval_budget)),
        "live ontology says {} has eval_budget `{}` but no generated \
         rules/lsp_max_*.toml file contains that pairing -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.eval_budget
    );
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("message = \"{}\"", rule.message)),
        "live ontology message for {} not found verbatim in any generated \
         rules/lsp_max_*.toml file -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id
    );
    assert!(
        toml_content.contains(&format!("rationale = \"{}\"", rule.rationale)),
        "live ontology rationale for {} not found verbatim in any generated \
         rules/lsp_max_*.toml file -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id
    );
}

fn assert_rule_in_md(md_content: &str, rule: &LiveRule) {
    assert!(
        md_content.contains(&format!("`{}`", rule.rule_id)),
        "live ontology has rule `{}` but docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md does not -- generated \
         catalog has drifted behind ontology.ttl",
        rule.rule_id
    );
    assert!(
        md_content.contains(rule.name),
        "live ontology says {} has name `{}` but docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md does not \
         contain it -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.name
    );
    assert!(
        md_content.contains(&format!("| {} |", rule.severity)),
        "live ontology says {} has severity `{}` but generated docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md \
         does not contain that cell -- drift detected",
        rule.rule_id, rule.severity
    );
    assert!(
        md_content.contains(rule.message),
        "live ontology message for {} not found verbatim in docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md -- \
         drift detected",
        rule.rule_id
    );
}

/// Floor sanity check: guards against a silently-broken or silently-empty
/// SPARQL query (e.g. a query engine regression, a typo in the query text
/// that still parses but matches nothing) making every loop-based assertion
/// below vacuously true. If this fails, the failure is in the query itself,
/// not in drift between two artifacts.
#[test]
fn sparql_query_returned_at_least_one_rule() {
    assert!(
        !LIVE_RULES.is_empty(),
        "the `rules` SPARQL query against ontology.ttl returned zero lm:LintRule rows -- \
         either the ontology lost every individual or the query itself is broken; every \
         other assertion in this file would otherwise pass vacuously"
    );
}

/// Row-count parity between what the live ontology says right now and what
/// is actually checked into `rules/lsp_max_*.toml` right now. Counts lines
/// that are EXACTLY `[[rules]]` (not merely containing that substring):
/// `rule_pack.toml.tmpl`'s own header comment prose ("One [[rules]] table
/// per file...") also contains the literal substring `[[rules]]` in every
/// generated file, so a naive `.matches("[[rules]]").count()` over the
/// whole file would double-count -- this discriminator was verified
/// against the real generated output before being trusted, not assumed
/// from the template source alone.
#[test]
fn rule_count_matches_generated_toml_files_right_now() {
    let toml_content = all_generated_rule_toml();
    let rule_count = toml_content
        .lines()
        .filter(|l| l.trim() == "[[rules]]")
        .count();
    assert_eq!(
        rule_count,
        LIVE_RULES.len(),
        "ontology.ttl has {} lm:LintRule individuals right now, but the checked-in \
         rules/lsp_max_*.toml files have {rule_count} real [[rules]] table headers total \
         -- the generated rule pack has drifted behind ontology.ttl",
        LIVE_RULES.len()
    );
}

/// The core check: every rule the live ontology reports right now is still
/// reflected, verbatim, in the artifacts as they actually sit on disk.
/// Failing here means the checked-in generated files no longer match
/// ontology.ttl -- exactly the silent-drift failure mode cap05's obligation
/// text names, and neither the hand-transcribed proof (which never
/// re-reads ontology.ttl after `rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl` was last hand-
/// edited) nor a plain `diff` against a stale copy would catch it.
#[test]
fn every_live_rule_matches_generated_artifacts_right_now() {
    let toml_content = all_generated_rule_toml();
    for rule in LIVE_RULES {
        assert_rule_in_toml(&toml_content, rule);
        assert_rule_in_md(MD_CONTENT, rule);
    }
}

/// `ORDER BY ?ruleId` in the live query is expected to sort lexically
/// ascending. This is a live regression guard on the query engine's own
/// collation (praxis-graphlaw or oxigraph, whichever backend answered this
/// sync), not a hand-asserted fact about how the array happens to be
/// typed -- if the engine's ORDER BY collation ever changes, this fails on
/// the very next sync instead of silently reordering the generated catalog
/// and having nothing notice. Scoped to `docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md` only --
/// see this file's module doc, "Honest scope", for why the fan-out
/// `rules/lsp_max_*.toml` files have no comparable single-file order to
/// check.
#[test]
fn live_row_order_is_lexical_ascending_by_rule_id_in_markdown_catalog() {
    let rule_ids: Vec<&str> = LIVE_RULES.iter().map(|r| r.rule_id).collect();
    let mut sorted_ids = rule_ids.clone();
    sorted_ids.sort_unstable();
    assert_eq!(
        rule_ids, sorted_ids,
        "LIVE_RULES is not in lexically-ascending ruleId order -- the query's own \
         `ORDER BY ?ruleId` did not produce sorted results this sync"
    );

    let md_offsets: Vec<usize> = sorted_ids
        .iter()
        .map(|id| {
            MD_CONTENT
                .find(&format!("`{id}`"))
                .unwrap_or_else(|| panic!("{id} present in generated docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md"))
        })
        .collect();
    let mut sorted_md_offsets = md_offsets.clone();
    sorted_md_offsets.sort_unstable();
    assert_eq!(
        md_offsets, sorted_md_offsets,
        "docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md row order does not match the live ontology's lexical \
         ruleId order"
    );
}

/// Negative sanity check: a fabricated rule id that does not exist in
/// `ontology.ttl` must not spuriously appear in either generated artifact.
/// Guards against a naive `contains()`-based check in this proof silently
/// matching everything.
#[test]
fn generated_artifacts_reject_unknown_rule_id() {
    let bogus = "LSPMAX-NOT-REAL-999";
    assert!(
        !all_generated_rule_toml().contains(bogus),
        "sanity: bogus rule id must not appear in generated rules/lsp_max_*.toml files"
    );
    assert!(
        !MD_CONTENT.contains(bogus),
        "sanity: bogus rule id must not appear in generated docs/lsp_max_rule_pack.md"
    );
}
